Hema-Québec celebrated his 10th anniversary of his foundation yesterday, and his president, Francine Décary, had reason to rejoice because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Above all, he regained the public's confidence that he had been seriously vaccinated by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and with the disillusionment of the public, in February 1994, the Government of Canada conducted a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations so that such a disaster would no longer occur.
While Judge Krever was late to present his report, certain provinces then formed a committee that aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the committee of Gélineau carried out this mission.
As a result of Gélineau and Krever's reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Hema-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to provide all other provinces and territories.
" In 1998, when Hema-Québec began its activities, almost 38 per cent of the people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalled Decary.
The situation was discouraging.
After much effort has been made to improve the safety of blood products and much work over the years that followed, we have recovered public confidence " , he said, before he said proudly that at the beginning of 2008, about 94 per cent of the Quebec population was in subsequent confidence in Hema-Québec.
Dr. Decary, however, recalls that " confidence is extremely fragile " .
Since its creation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of many cases of the human variant of the disease of the cow, a new variant of the disease of Creutzfeldt-Jakob, account Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we support one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, which, when we do not know it and when a serious disease can arise from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we establish exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we refused the blood of people who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But a few years ago, it has been demonstrated beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle applied was meaningful."
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: the nuclear acid tests that allow donors to detect directly in their blood the presence of the virus and not the anti-virus antibodies, in which the tests used have so far been based.
Nuclear acid tests allowed the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We can reduce this period for a period of less than one week.
We therefore substantially reduce the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements allowed a significant reduction in the risk of contracting AIDS by blood transfusions.
Today, every 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV - contaminated blood.
"That means that you will have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone is infected with HIV.
As Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before it can overcome a case of HIV transmission by a blood product.
I believe that today it is possible to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worry," says Hema-Québec's head.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
It's never known which pathogen could emerge from the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of the Reunion which, for example, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
Hema-Québec must be constantly vigilant ", pursued by Dr. Décary before he underlined that in addition to a safe supply, hema-Québec should also provide for sufficient supply.
" The needs increase because the elderly population.
