Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
In the world some 50 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and chronic liver disease in Hungary is considered one of the main causes of death.
The number of infections in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many patients do not know that they are infected.
The name of hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; they are characteristic of liver infection and icterity, but their pathogenic agents and the occasional diseases are very different.
Hepatitis virus depending on the pathogen is spread through two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humour (sperm, vaginal humour, saliva).
Travelers are recommended to be protected by vaccine against viruses A and B, against C no vaccines are available.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two or three weeks after consumption of the infected food, manifested by a general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this they appear in the skin and in the white of the eyes, icterity, excretion becomes clear, dark color urine and treatment may last even two - three weeks.
Each year, one million people die in the world from cancer and hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: without treatment it may cause hepatitis C and even cancer.
Most of the infected do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent in the form of pautine destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early recognition, systematic medical control is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can also be discovered with routine laboratory control, it is worth consulting your family doctor when you experience some unknown symptoms.
The disease is treated if it is discovered in time, it is possible to eliminate the organism's virus, thus eliminating the infection and preventing cancer.
On 30 September, the World Day of Hepatitis was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients.
Its objective is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of early recognition.
